 Monday, July 26, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, July 25: Driven by Tata Motors and Ashok Leyland, commercial vehicle sales went up by a whopping 43.2 per cent during the first quarter of this fiscal. A total of 66,866 units were sold during April-June over 46,667 units sold in the year-ago period, data compiled by SIAM showed. Sales of medium and heavy buses and trucks surged 48 per cent at 40,855 units, while that of light commercial vehicles grew 36.4 per cent at 26,011 units. Sales of medium and heavy buses and trucks surged 48 per cent to 40,855 units, while those of light commercial vehicles jumped 36.4 per cent to 26,011 units.																								 New Delhi, July 25: Tata Consultancy Services (TCS) will have to dip into its internal resources for a minimum of Rs 250 crore to pay parent company Tata Sons for transfer of assets. Existing shareholders, including Tata Sons, are putting up for sale about 3.267 crore shares in its IPO of 5.54 crore shares. Only 2.277 crore shares will be issued afresh. TCS will have to pay Rs 2,300 crore for the transfer of assets.																								 New Delhi, July 25: Luxury carmaker DaimlerChrysler India has firmed up plans to foray into commercial vehicles with the launch of Actros trucks by year-end, said company chief Hans-Michael Huber.																								 Mumbai, July 25: The Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) has slapped special margins on 19 stocks, including Alka Spinners and Kirloskar Brothers from tomorrow.																								 Mumbai, July 25: ONGCs deep-water drilling campaign has crossed 3,000 meters water depth, making it the second operator in the world to achieve the feat.
